This simplifies to checking if \( 10n - 9 + 7 \leq 10n \), which is always true. Therefore, every set will contain the next multiple of 7 after the starting number. 4. **Checking Divisibility**: - We need to find how many starting numbers \( s = 10n - 9 \) are divisible by 7. This translates to solving \( 10n - 9 \equiv 0 \pmod{7} \). - Simplifying, we get \( 10n \equiv 9 \pmod{7} \). Since \( 10 \equiv 3 \pmod{7} \), we have \( 3n \equiv 2 \pmod{7} \). The multiplicative inverse of 3 modulo 7 is 5, so \( n \equiv 2 \times 5 \equiv 3 \pmod{7} \). 5. **Counting Valid \( n \)**: - The valid \( n \) are those congruent to 3 modulo 7. These values are \( n = 3, 10, 17, \ldots, 94 \). - The sequence \( 3, 10, 17, \ldots, 94 \) has 14 terms (since \( 94 = 3 + 7 \times 13 \)). Thus, the number of sets containing exactly two multiples of 7 is \(\boxed{14}\).
